Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon in quantum mechanics where two or more particles become interconnected in such a way that the state of one particle cannot be described independently of the state of the other(s), even when the particles are separated by large distances. This means that the measurement of a property (such as spin, position, or polarization) of one particle will instantaneously affect the state of the other particle(s).

Entanglement is a key feature of quantum mechanics that has no classical counterpart. It leads to correlations between the particles that are stronger than what can be explained by classical physics. For example, if two particles are entangled, measuring the spin of one particle will immediately determine the spin of the other particle, regardless of the distance separating them.

This phenomenon has profound implications for our understanding of the nature of reality and has been experimentally verified in numerous experiments, such as those testing Bell's theorem. Quantum entanglement is also a fundamental resource for emerging technologies, including quantum computing and quantum cryptography, which leverage these unique correlations for processing information in ways that classical systems cannot achieve.
